<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="50" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,266,612]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,346,372]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Remarks.</emphasis>
The only specimen examined is provisionally identified as 
<taxonomicName box="[1020,1229,346,371]" class="Bivalvia" family="Thyasiridae" genus="Thyasira" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lucinoida" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tortuosa">
<emphasis box="[1020,1229,346,371]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Thyasira tortuosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and has the characteristically compressed and anteriorly expanded outline noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Payne" box="[958,1246,386,412]" pageId="9" pageNumber="55" refString="Payne, C. M. &amp; Allen, J. A. (1991) The morphology of deep-sea Thyasiridae (Mollusca: Bivalvia) from the Atlantic Ocean. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B, 334, 481 - 562." type="journal article" year="1991">
Payne and Allen (
<number box="[1174,1237,386,412]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" value="1991.0">1991</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The shell from Gulf of Cadiz (
<quantity box="[329,422,426,452]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
) is much larger than any of the shells described by these authors (
<quantity box="[1202,1295,426,452]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
) and comes from a greater depth: 
<quantity box="[403,484,466,492]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.9019999999999997" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="3902.0">3902m</quantity>
whilst the maximum given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Payne" box="[846,1105,466,492]" pageId="9" pageNumber="55" refString="Payne, C. M. &amp; Allen, J. A. (1991) The morphology of deep-sea Thyasiridae (Mollusca: Bivalvia) from the Atlantic Ocean. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B, 334, 481 - 562." type="journal article" year="1991">
Payne &amp; Allen (
<number box="[1035,1096,466,492]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" value="1991.0">1991</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
was 
<quantity box="[1164,1256,466,492]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.359" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="2359.0">2359 m</quantity>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Dufour" box="[1266,1436,466,492]" pageId="9" pageNumber="54" refString="Dufour, S. (2005) Gill anatomy and the evolution of symbiosis in the bivalve family Thyasiridae. Biological Bulletin, 208, 200 - 212." type="journal article" year="2005">
Dufour (
<number box="[1366,1428,466,492]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" value="2005.0">2005</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
did not examine this species but the Gulf of Cadiz specimen has a 
<typeStatus box="[920,978,506,532]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Type</typeStatus>
<number box="[985,999,506,532]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
gill with both demibranchs. The gills are rather thick and have the same appearance as the ones that exhibit strong bacterial symbiosis such as 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Thyasiridae" genus="Thyasira" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lucinoida" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="flexu">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">T. flexu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
osa and 
<taxonomicName box="[304,407,586,611]" class="Bivalvia" family="Thyasiridae" genus="Thyasira" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lucinoida" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="gouldi">
<emphasis box="[304,407,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">T. gouldi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
